# ROS2 DDS Distributed Benchmark

## Overview

This workspace implements a ROS2 benchmark for evaluating DDS behavior with many simulated sensors, distributed central subscribers and automatic CSV aggregation.

The system supports:

* Multi-topic publishing
* Multi-instance central subscribers
* Distributed benchmark collection
* Start signal synchronization
* Automatic CSV merge
* Loss, latency and jitter analysis

---

## Docker

The ROS2 environment is expected to run inside a Docker container. Build and run the workspace from inside the container, not from the host machine.

Create the container, mounting this workspace into `/root/ros2_ws`:

```bash
docker run -it \
  --name ros2_humble \
  --network host \
  -v "/home/praticap/ros2:/root/ros2_ws" \
  osrf/ros:humble-desktop
```

Enter an existing container:

```bash
docker exec -it ros2_humble /bin/bash
```

Inside the container:

```bash
cd /root/ros2_ws
. run_script.sh
./clean_build.sh
```

If the container already exists but is stopped:

```bash
docker start ros2_humble
docker exec -it ros2_humble /bin/bash
```

---

## Benchmark Start Synchronization

Synchronization is controlled by a ROS2 start signal:

```text
/benchmark_start_signal
```

Only `node_central` with:

```text
instance_id = 0
```

publishes the start signal.

Every sensor and central node subscribes to this signal. When the signal is received, each node computes:

```text
benchmark_start = now + 5 seconds
```

The benchmark then runs until:

```text
benchmark_start + benchmark_duration_sec
```

The central instance `0` publishes the start signal repeatedly for a few seconds so nodes that are already starting up still receive it. The topic uses transient local QoS.

---

## Central Subscriber

Run:

```bash
ros2 run node_central node_central
```

Parameters:

| Parameter                | Type   | Default | Description                                      |
| ------------------------ | ------ | ------- | ------------------------------------------------ |
| `instance_id`            | int    | `0`     | Subscriber instance identifier                   |
| `instance_count`         | int    | `1`     | Total subscriber instances                       |
| `benchmark_number`       | string | `-1`    | Benchmark execution identifier                   |
| `sensor_count`           | string | `0`     | Total sensor count identifier for CSV filenames  |
| `benchmark_duration_sec` | int    | `180`   | Benchmark duration after scheduled start         |
| `start_signal_delay_sec` | int    | `1`     | Delay before instance `0` starts publishing start |

Each central instance listens to:

```text
CassioData_<instance_id>
```

Example:

```text
Instance 0 -> CassioData_0
Instance 1 -> CassioData_1
Instance 2 -> CassioData_2
```

---

## Sensor Publisher

Run:

```bash
ros2 run cassio_driver sensor_node
```

Parameters:

| Parameter                | Type | Default | Description                         |
| ------------------------ | ---- | ------- | ----------------------------------- |
| `sensor_count`           | int  | `1`     | Number of simulated sensors         |
| `publish_rate_hz`        | int  | `100`   | Publish rate per sensor             |
| `payload_size_kb`        | int  | `20`    | Payload size per message            |
| `hardware_id`            | int  | `1`     | Physical/container identifier       |
| `instance_count`         | int  | `1`     | Number of distributed topics        |
| `benchmark_duration_sec` | int  | `180`   | Benchmark duration after start      |

Sensors are automatically distributed across topics:

```text
CassioData_0
CassioData_1
CassioData_2
...
```

using:

```cpp
hash(sensor_name) % instance_count
```

Publishers wait for `/benchmark_start_signal`, schedule `now + 5s`, publish until `benchmark_duration_sec`, then shut down automatically.

---

## Recommended Test

This example runs:

```text
100 sensors @ 100 Hz @ 20 KB payload
5 central subscriber instances
180 seconds benchmark duration
```

Open one shell per command inside the Docker container.

In every shell:

```bash
cd /root/ros2_ws
. run_script.sh
```

Recommended order:

1. Start central instances `1` to `4`.
2. Start the sensor publisher.
3. Start central instance `0`.

This makes the start signal happen after all other processes are already waiting. If instance `0` is started first, increase `start_signal_delay_sec`.

Start central instance `1`:

```bash
ros2 run node_central node_central \
  --ros-args \
  -p instance_id:=1 \
  -p instance_count:=5 \
  -p benchmark_number:=\"0\" \
  -p sensor_count:=\"100\" \
  -p benchmark_duration_sec:=180
```

Start central instance `2`:

```bash
ros2 run node_central node_central \
  --ros-args \
  -p instance_id:=2 \
  -p instance_count:=5 \
  -p benchmark_number:=\"0\" \
  -p sensor_count:=\"100\" \
  -p benchmark_duration_sec:=180
```

Start central instance `3`:

```bash
ros2 run node_central node_central \
  --ros-args \
  -p instance_id:=3 \
  -p instance_count:=5 \
  -p benchmark_number:=\"0\" \
  -p sensor_count:=\"100\" \
  -p benchmark_duration_sec:=180
```

Start central instance `4`:

```bash
ros2 run node_central node_central \
  --ros-args \
  -p instance_id:=4 \
  -p instance_count:=5 \
  -p benchmark_number:=\"0\" \
  -p sensor_count:=\"100\" \
  -p benchmark_duration_sec:=180
```

Start the sensor publisher:

```bash
ros2 run cassio_driver sensor_node \
  --ros-args \
  -p sensor_count:=100 \
  -p publish_rate_hz:=100 \
  -p payload_size_kb:=20 \
  -p hardware_id:=1 \
  -p instance_count:=5 \
  -p benchmark_duration_sec:=180
```

Start central instance `0`. This one sends the start signal:

```bash
ros2 run node_central node_central \
  --ros-args \
  -p instance_id:=0 \
  -p instance_count:=5 \
  -p benchmark_number:=\"0\" \
  -p sensor_count:=\"100\" \
  -p benchmark_duration_sec:=180 \
  -p start_signal_delay_sec:=3
```

---

## CSV Generation

Each central instance generates a temporary CSV:

```text
benchmarks/tmp/benchmark_<sensor_count>_<benchmark_number>_instance_<id>.tmp.csv
```

After all instances finish:

* Instance `0` waits for all `.done` files
* Instance `0` merges all temporary CSVs
* Temporary files are removed
* A final consolidated benchmark CSV is generated

Final CSV:

```text
benchmarks/benchmark_results_<sensor_count>_<benchmark_number>.csv
```

---

## Benchmark Metrics

The distributed subscriber framework computes:

* Message loss
* Loss percentage
* Average latency
* Maximum latency
* Average jitter
* Maximum jitter
* Received messages per sensor

Each CSV row also contains:

* `instance_id`
* `sensor_name`

---

## Benchmark Flow

```text
Central instance 0 publishes /benchmark_start_signal
        ↓
Publishers and subscribers receive signal
        ↓
Each node schedules start = now + 5s
        ↓
Publishers start publishing
        ↓
Subscribers collect metrics
        ↓
Publishers stop after benchmark_duration_sec
        ↓
Subscribers stop after benchmark_duration_sec
        ↓
Temporary CSVs generated
        ↓
Instance 0 merges CSVs
        ↓
Final consolidated benchmark saved
```

---

## Useful Commands

Rebuild only the project packages:

```bash
./clean_build.sh
```

Check the start signal topic:

```bash
ros2 topic info /benchmark_start_signal
```

Check data topics:

```bash
ros2 topic list | grep CassioData
```

zip -r ros2.zip \
  cassio_interface cassio_driver node_central scripts readme run_script.sh clean_build.sh \
  -x '*/build/*' '*/install/*' '*/log/*' '*/benchmarks/*' '*.zip'

